<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910121-0112</DOCNO><DOCID>910121-0112.</DOCID><HL>   Oliver's Stores   Former Officers   Sued by SEC   ----   By Wade Lambert   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal</HL><DATE>01/21/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B5B</SO><IN>SECURITIES REGULATIONS AND ENFORCEMENTS (RGU)SPECIALTY APPAREL RETAILERS (SAP)</IN><GV>SECURITIES AND EXCHANGE COMMISSION (SEC)</GV><LP>   NEW YORK -- The Securities and Exchange Commission filed acivil suit against the former chief executive officer and theformer president of Oliver's Stores Inc., asking that each beordered to turn over $690,456 in alleged inside-tradingprofits.   The suit, filed in federal court in Manhattan, accusesformer Oliver's Chief Executive Joseph Wolfer and formerPresident Thomas Nadler of fraud and insider trading in analleged scheme to inflate Oliver's financial records andconceal problems at the company. Mr. Wolfer, of Creskill,N.J., and Mr. Nadler, of Franklin Lakes, N.J., wereco-founders of Oliver's.</LP><TEXT>   Oliver's, a discount clothing chain based in Ridgefield,N.J., filed for bankruptcy-law protection in March 1987 afterthe alleged scheme unraveled, the SEC said in the lawsuit.   The SEC also asked the court to order that Mr. Wolfer andMr. Nadler each pay an additional penalty of as much as $2million for the alleged insider-trading.   Mr. Wolfer pleaded guilty last year in federal court inNewark, N.J., to conspiracy and fraud in connection with theOliver's allegations. Mr. Nadler pleaded guilty to conspiracyand securities-law violations.   Mr. Wolfer and Mr. Nadler haven't settled the SEC civilsuits. Attorneys for the pair couldn't be reached forcomment.   The SEC said that three other defendants accused ofsecurities-law violations in connection with the allegedscheme at Oliver's settled with the commission. In thesettlements, the defendants neither admitted nor denied anywrongdoing.   Jack Trachtman, of Livingston, N.J., former Oliver'sStores vice president, settled the SEC lawsuit against him byagreeing to pay $65,775 and consenting to a permanentinjunction barring him future securities-law violations. The$65,775 represents the amount of losses that Mr. Trachtmanallegedly avoided by trading on inside information aboutproblems at Oliver's, the SEC said in its lawsuit againsthim.   Raymond Bacek, of Boonton, N.J., former Oliver's Storescontroller and chief financial officer, settled theallegations against him by agreeing to a permanent injunctionagainst future securities-law violations. Robert Horowitz, ofEast Northport, N.Y., president of closely held MaspethIndustries Inc., also settled the allegations against him byagreeing to a permanent injunction. The SEC said that as partof the alleged scheme, fictitious bulk sales to Maspeth wererecorded in Oliver's books to boost revenue.   Last year, Mr. Bacek pleaded guilty to criminal charges ofconspiracy and fraud in connection with the alleged Oliver'sscheme. Stephen Dratch, an attorney for Mr. Bacek, said thesettlement was part of an agreement reached with the SEC andthe U.S. attorney's office in Newark in early 1987 when Mr.Bacek began cooperating with the investigation. Mr. Bacek wasgiven a suspended sentence and three years probation lastyear.   Howard Stave, an attorney for Mr. Horowitz, said, &quot;Thesettlement speaks for itself.&quot; Attorneys for the otherdefendants couldn't be reached for comment.</TEXT></DOC>